## Architecture Rules

### Backend
- One module per feature domain — no cross-domain imports except through explicit interfaces
- Controllers are thin — all business logic lives in services
- All calls to external APIs go through a single typed client — never call external APIs directly from domain services
- Environment config via `ConfigService` only — never `process.env` directly
- No hardcoded external URLs, IDs, or credentials — always from config
- No N+1 queries — related data fetched in bulk
- All unbounded queries require a `where` clause or explicit pagination
- Every external HTTP call has an explicit timeout (default 5s)
- All inbound DTOs are validated at the controller boundary — never trust raw request bodies
- Mutating endpoints that may be retried support an idempotency key

### Frontend
- All API calls through a single typed wrapper in `lib/api.ts`
- State stores in `store/` — one file per concern; mutations only via defined actions
- No logic in page components — delegate to services or custom hooks
- Components with large data tables must use `useMemo` for derived calculations
- Server Components by default in Next.js App Router; Client Components only when interactivity requires
- No `useEffect` for data fetching — use Server Components or a query library
- Every async UI has explicit loading and error states

### Infrastructure (IaC)
- All infrastructure is declarative and committed to version control — no imperative scripts mutating shared environments
- Remote state with locking is mandatory for any shared environment — no `backend "local"` outside throwaway sandboxes
- Environments differ only by variables, not by resource definitions
- Every cloud resource carries the standard tags: `owner`, `env`, `service`, `cost-center`, `managed-by`
- Provider and module versions are pinned (`~>` for minor on providers, exact for registry modules)
- Secrets never appear in `.tf`, `.tfvars`, plan output, or state outputs — always referenced from the secrets manager by ID/ARN
- Apply is performed only by CI against shared environments — no developer laptops applying to staging/prod
- IAM policies start from deny; resource-level scoping required; no `*` action on `*` resource

### TypeScript
- Strict mode throughout — no `any`, no implicit returns
- `readonly` by default on class fields and array/tuple types where mutation isn't required
- Discriminated unions over optional flags for state representation
- `as const` object literals + derived union type instead of `enum`
- Explicit return types on all exported functions and class methods

### Observability
- Structured logging only — no `console.log` in production paths
- Every request gets a correlation/request ID propagated to downstream calls
- Log at boundaries: request in, request out, external call in, external call out
- Log levels: `error` (actionable), `warn` (degraded), `info` (state change), `debug` (diagnostic)
- Never log secrets, tokens, full Authorization headers, or PII

